<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does ice maker repair cost in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Our diagnostic fee is $89, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most residential ice maker repairs run between $120 and $280. A water inlet valve, water filter, or bin sensor replacement is toward the lower end. Control board issues or sealed system work run higher. On luxury standalone units like Scotsman or Sub-Zero, parts costs are higher — we provide a written estimate before any work begins."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My ice maker stopped making ice completely — what's the most likely cause?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The water inlet valve is the most common culprit — it controls water flow into the ice maker, and when it fails or gets blocked with mineral scale, no water enters and no ice is made. Other likely causes: a clogged water filter restricting flow, a failed ice maker module or control board, or a frozen water line. In LA's hard water environment, mineral scale in the inlet valve is more common than in most cities. We check the valve and filter first."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My ice is coming out cloudy or small — is the ice maker broken?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Not necessarily. Cloudy, small, or misshapen ice is almost always a water quality issue, not a machine malfunction. Los Angeles has among the hardest municipal water in the country — high mineral content produces cloudy ice and can cause scale buildup inside the ice maker that reduces the size of cubes. If the machine is producing ice but it looks wrong, we inspect the water line, inlet valve screen, and ice mold for mineral deposits before concluding the machine itself has failed."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair standalone undercounter ice makers like Scotsman and Sub-Zero?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Standalone undercounter ice makers — Scotsman, Sub-Zero, True, Hoshizaki, U-Line — are a significant part of what we service in LA's premium home market. These units require brand-specific OEM parts and a different diagnostic approach than refrigerator-mounted ice makers. We carry parts for Sub-Zero and service the other luxury brands with parts sourced from authorized distributors."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My ice maker is leaking water onto the floor — what's wrong?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A leaking ice maker usually has one of three causes: a failed water inlet valve that won't close fully and drips continuously, a cracked or loose water supply line connection, or a clogged drain line that backs up and overflows. On standalone undercounter units, a clogged drain is the most frequent cause — these units generate warm, humid exhaust that can cause algae and scale growth in the drain. We locate the source before replacing anything."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often should an ice maker be cleaned and descaled?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "In Los Angeles specifically — every 6 months. LA's hard water (typically 300+ mg/L total dissolved solids) deposits mineral scale inside ice makers faster than in most US cities. Scale accumulates in the water inlet valve screen, the ice mold, the evaporator, and the water lines. It affects ice clarity, ice size, and eventually machine operation. Standalone units like Scotsman recommend descaling every 6 months as a maintenance standard. We offer a descaling service alongside repair calls."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does the 90-day warranty cover on ice maker repairs?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Every ice maker repair we complete carries a 90-day warranty on both parts and labor. If the same issue returns within that window, we come back at no charge. That's in writing before we leave."
      }
    }
  ]
}
