<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="intro-grid">
      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-number">01 — About This Service</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">A lot of "broken" ice makers in LA aren't broken — they're scaled.</h2>

        <p>Ice maker calls in Los Angeles split into two categories: actual machine failure, and LA's hard water doing what hard water does. The city's municipal water supply runs at 300–400 mg/L total dissolved solids — well into "very hard" territory. That mineral content deposits scale in the water inlet valve screen, coats the water lines and ice mold, and over months reduces ice production, makes cubes cloudy and small, and eventually blocks flow entirely. Many homeowners call us convinced the machine has failed. Sometimes it has. Often, it's the water.</p>

        <p>Our technicians check both. On every ice maker call we inspect the water inlet valve for mineral scale, the water filter for restriction, and the water line for blockage before concluding there's a mechanical failure. If the machine itself has failed — water inlet valve gone, control board dead, bin sensor faulty, thermostat failed — we carry parts for the brands we see most in LA and can usually complete the repair same visit.</p>

        <p>The second category is luxury standalone undercounter ice makers — Scotsman, Sub-Zero, True, U-Line. These are common in Beverly Hills, Malibu, and the entertaining kitchens across LA's Westside. They require a different approach than a refrigerator-mounted ice maker: different parts, different water quality requirements, and a different maintenance schedule. We service them and carry OEM parts for Sub-Zero specifically.</p>

        <div class="tip-blue">
          <div class="tip-label">💧 LA Water Note</div>
          <p>LA's hard water affects every ice maker in the city, but standalone undercounter units are most vulnerable — they run more cycles per day and have more exposed water contact surfaces than fridge-mounted makers. Scotsman and other premium brands recommend descaling every 6 months in hard water areas. We include a descaling inspection with every ice maker service call.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

