<!-- 11 FAQ -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">09 — Frequently Asked Questions</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Ice maker repair — what people ask us</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How much does ice maker repair cost in Los Angeles?</h3>
        <p>Our diagnostic fee is $89, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most residential ice maker repairs run between $120 and $280. A water inlet valve, water filter, or bin sensor replacement is toward the lower end. Control board issues or sealed system work on standalone units run higher — we provide a written estimate before any work begins.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My ice maker stopped making ice completely — what's the most likely cause?</h3>
        <p>The water inlet valve is the most common mechanical cause — when blocked with mineral scale or electrically failed, no water enters and no ice is made. Also check the water filter (replace every 6 months), a frozen water line, a failed ice maker module, or the wire arm in the OFF position. In LA's hard water environment, mineral scale in the inlet valve is more common than in most cities.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My ice is coming out cloudy or small — is the ice maker broken?</h3>
        <p>Not necessarily. Cloudy, small, or misshapen ice is almost always a water quality issue in Los Angeles. High mineral content produces cloudy ice and can cause scale buildup in the ice mold that changes cube shape. If the machine is cycling normally but ice quality is poor, we check the water supply first before assuming the machine needs parts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do you repair standalone undercounter ice makers like Scotsman and Sub-Zero?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Standalone undercounter ice makers are a significant part of what we service in LA's premium home market. These units require brand-specific OEM parts and a different diagnostic approach than refrigerator-mounted ice makers. We carry parts for Sub-Zero and service Scotsman, Hoshizaki, U-Line, and True with parts from authorized distributors.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How often should an ice maker be cleaned and descaled?</h3>
        <p>In Los Angeles specifically — every 6 months. LA's hard water (typically 300+ mg/L TDS) deposits mineral scale faster than most US cities. Scale affects ice clarity, size, and eventually machine operation. Standalone units like Scotsman recommend 6-month descaling as a maintenance standard for hard water areas. We include a descaling inspection with every ice maker service call.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My ice maker is leaking water — what's wrong?</h3>
        <p>Three most likely causes: a failed water inlet valve that won't shut off fully and drips continuously, a cracked or loose water supply line connection, or a clogged drain line on standalone units that backs up and overflows. We locate the actual leak source before recommending any parts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What does the 90-day warranty cover on ice maker repairs?</h3>
        <p>Every ice maker repair we complete carries a 90-day warranty on both parts and labor. If the same issue returns within that window, we come back at no charge. That's in writing before we leave.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

